default&#xa0;
defaultThrough
default our research into girls’ attitudes, the Youth Sport Trust
default has found that many girls do not
default enjoy sport ‘for s
defaultport’s sake’.
default We believe that one of the key
defaults to making PE 
defaultand 
defaultsport a priority for those girls 
defaultis 
defaultto ensure that both are relevant to girls’ 
defaultinterests. For example, PE with a clearl
defaulty articulated purpose such as
default develop
defaulting confidence, enhancing body image, improving health or preparing
default for a set-piece performance
default or charity fundraising event
default, is much more likely to engage girls effectively. 
defaultIn t
defaulthis sense these outcomes should not be seen as by-products of PE and school sport, but as planned outcomes of both. 
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultCrucially, the Youth Sport Trust be
defaultlieves that, in order to 
defaulteffectively ‘market’
default PE and school sport to all girls, schools need to unders
defaulttand what motivates their female pupils to take part in PE, and to be physically active. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs mentioned above, t
defaulthrough our 
defaultGirls PE and Sport Innovation project
default, the Youth Sport Trust is working with 21 schools around the country to help them
default better engage 
default11-14 year old girls in PE and sport, and
default drive up participation rates. The project provides schools with training, res
defaultources and ongoing support to help them review their PE and sport culture and
default develop innovative
default practices to ensure they 
defaultare relevant and attractive to girls. A key part of this process is encouraging schools to establish Girls Leadership and Marketing groups (or 
defaultGLAMS), made up of a cross-section of female pupils, which establish girls’ motivations, and influence delivery w
defaultithin the school. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Fit for Girls programme, mentioned above a
defaultnd
default delivered in 
defaultpartnership with 
defaultsportdefaultscotland
default 
defaulthas
default been highly successful
default 
defaultin encouraging
default PE staff to carry out consultation 
defaultwith their female pupils, with 98.8% 
defaultof PE staff who have taken 
defaultpart
default in the programme reporting that they undertook such a consultation. 
defaultMeanwhile, 60% of PE staff reported that Fit for Girls had helped to increase girls' participation in PE, sport and physical activity. In particular, those who were involved in Fit fo
defaultr Girls noted that it helped to remove barriers to girls taking part in PE and sport and increase their confidence and enthusiasm for the subject.
default&#xa0;
defaultFit for Girls 
defaulthas start
defaulted to create a culture change in
default PE, physical activity and sport engagement for adole
defaultscent girls in schools. Building on this learning, Fit for Girls is now offering schools the opportunity to engage with a Fit for Girls trainer in a bespoke 1:1 
defaultapproach in order t
defaulto allow discussions and solutions to be individually tailored to meet school
default needs.  
