default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition the Youth Sport Trust believes that schools should be encouraged to develop their own female sporting role models. With a lack of positive role models in the media, older girls in school can serve as strong role models for younger girls, demons
defaulttrating the realistic possibilities of what they can achieve. 
defaultA crucial element of the Youth Sport Trust’s Girls PE and Innovation project, is that the ‘GLAMS’ mentioned above also act as role models to younger girls and help to ‘sell’ participation in PE 
defaultand school sport. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultResearch shows that boys are more likely than girls to prefer school sport or physical activity to be competitive
default.
default In order to engage all young people, including girls, in competition, it is imperative that sporting formats are fully inclusive, and the wider benefits of taking part are emphasised to young people and school sport practitioners. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, while som
defaulte girls find traditional, confrontational, models of competition off-putting, research shows they are more likely to engage in personal or group challenge activities
default. The Youth Sport Trust therefore believes that government and practitioners should employ
default a diverse approach which values different forms of competition equally. 
